## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept of **alert fatigue** clicked for me today in a way I had not fully appreciated before. Alert fatigue is what happens when a monitoring system generates so many alerts — many of them low-priority or false positives — that the people responsible for reviewing them stop paying attention. The alerts keep coming, the queue keeps growing, and the genuinely important signals get lost in the noise.

Alert fatigue is not just a minor operational inconvenience. It is a security failure mode. The Capital One breach I covered on Day 16 and Day 28 involved GuardDuty alerts that were not acted on promptly. Part of the reason alerts do not get acted on is that the people responsible for reviewing them are overwhelmed by volume and have stopped treating each alert with appropriate urgency.

The solution to alert fatigue is not fewer monitoring tools — it is better tuned monitoring. That means configuring tools to surface the right signals at the right severity level, grouping related alerts into coherent findings rather than generating dozens of individual notifications, and establishing clear ownership so that every alert has a named person responsible for reviewing and acting on it within a defined timeframe.

This is a design challenge as much as a technical one, and it is something I want to think carefully about in the monitoring strategy for OpenMRS.

