## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2021 Scripps Health ransomware attack** — which I mentioned briefly on Day 17 but want to revisit specifically through the continuous monitoring lens.

Scripps Health's network was offline for nearly a month following the attack, affecting care delivery across multiple facilities and ultimately costing approximately $113 million. Post-incident reporting indicated that the attackers had been present in the network for some time before the ransomware was deployed — a pattern known as dwell time, where attackers move laterally through a network and establish persistence before triggering their final payload.

Extended dwell time — attackers present in a network for days or weeks before detection — is one of the clearest indicators of a continuous monitoring failure. A functioning monitoring program with properly tuned GuardDuty, regular log reviews, and defined alert escalation processes should surface the indicators of lateral movement before an attacker can establish the access needed to deploy ransomware across the entire environment.

The Scripps Health attack cost $113 million and disrupted care for tens of thousands of patients. A continuous monitoring strategy that detected the initial compromise earlier in the attack chain would not necessarily have prevented the intrusion — but it could have dramatically reduced the dwell time, limited the scope of the damage, and potentially prevented the full-scale ransomware deployment.

That is the value proposition of continuous monitoring in concrete terms: not perfect prevention, but dramatically faster detection and response that limits the blast radius of incidents that do occur.

