## The Challenge of Continuous Monitoring in Resource-Constrained Environments

I want to be honest about something that this strategy does not fully resolve: the resource requirement.

The monitoring schedule I documented above — daily GuardDuty reviews, weekly application log reviews, monthly vulnerability scans, quarterly access reviews and restoration tests — requires consistent time and attention from the ISSO and System Owner. For a small healthcare organization where those roles may be part-time or combined with other responsibilities, that commitment is genuinely challenging.

The risk of an under-resourced monitoring program is not just that some monitoring activities get skipped. It is that the program loses credibility — alerts pile up unreviewed, findings go unresolved, and the monitoring infrastructure becomes a compliance artifact rather than a security function. That is worse than a simpler program that is actually executed consistently.

I think the answer for resource-constrained organizations involves two things: automation wherever possible — automated backup validation, automated Config compliance checks, automated alerting for high-priority events — and ruthless prioritization of the manual activities that actually require human judgment. Daily review of every GuardDuty finding may not be realistic. Daily review of High and Critical findings, with weekly catch-up on Medium findings, might be. The strategy needs to be honest about what is actually achievable with available resources.

